<span id="freeTextContainer6770612405075224748">Read in full in the wake of finishing Byung-Chul Han’s <i>Psychopolitics</i>, and the whole seems less striking than the parts assigned to undergrads. Foucault’s language is opaque but playfully so and not as hard to understand as his reputation suggests. The work’s main weakness is that the same dozen ideas are repeated again and again, in so many ways, without being nuanced or backed up by empirical evidence. As history it’s paper thin, and as theory it’s dated, full of ideas that by now have been fu</span>
  <span id="freeText6770612405075224748" style="display:none">Read in full in the wake of finishing Byung-Chul Han’s <i>Psychopolitics</i>, and the whole seems less striking than the parts assigned to undergrads. Foucault’s language is opaque but playfully so and not as hard to understand as his reputation suggests. The work’s main weakness is that the same dozen ideas are repeated again and again, in so many ways, without being nuanced or backed up by empirical evidence. As history it’s paper thin, and as theory it’s dated, full of ideas that by now have been fully absorbed into the mainstream.</span>
